ed $20,000 to Oberlin in her will; husband James funded Talcott Hall women's dormitory in 1887.","relationship":"donor"},{"institution_id":"INST110","relationship":"founder","years":"1889-1921","institution_blurb":"One of eleven charter female trustees who launched the school in 1889; endowed a $100,000 chair in Bible study and served thirty-two years on the board."}],"bio":{"display_name":"Henrietta E Francis Talcott","first_name":"Henrietta","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":["Talcott"],"middle_name":"E","maiden_name":"Francis","photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777579864/Henrietta_Talcott_bir9r8.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"research_sources":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"henrietta-francis-1842"},"H03207":{"id":"H03207","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":7,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_easter_egg":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"is_progenitor":false},"birth":{"year":1835,"month":2,"day":7,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1916,"month":8,"day":21,"city":"Lake Mohonk","county":"Ulster","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"parents":{"father_id":"H01789","mother_id":"U00037"},"tags":["businessman","hooker_talcott_descent","politician"],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — James Talcott","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Talcott"},{"label":"James Talcott Inc. — 2019 Inductee profile"},{"label":"The NY Trust — James Talcott profile","url":"https://thenytrust.org/news/james-talcott/"},{"label":"Grokipedia — James Talcott","url":"https://grokipedia.com/page/james_talcott"}],"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"U00038","children_ids":["T01463","T01464","T01465","T01466","T01467"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1860,"date_month":10,"date_day":31,"location_state":"Connecticut","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1916}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["business"],"notable_blurb":"Founded James Talcott Inc., 19th-century factoring giant","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM026","landmark_blurb":"He leased the Jay Estate 1891-1904 after 159 years of Jay ownership."}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"family_connection","related_id":"T01459","display_label":"His nephew Allen Butler Talcott founded the Old Lyme colony.","link_text":"Allen Butler Talcott"}],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM025","plot_notes":"Cedar Hill Cemetery Hartford CT. Wikipedia and FindAGrave confirm."},"residence":{"city":"Manhattan","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"is_placeholder":false,"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST077","institution_blurb":"Funded Talcott Hall women's dormitory (1887)."}],"research_sources":[],"research_tags":[],"artworks":[],"documents":[],"quotes":[],"statues":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Wheelbarrow of underwear at eighteen, millionaire by thirty","body":"In 1854, eighteen-year-old James Talcott arrived in New York City pushing a wheelbarrow of undergarment samples for his brother's knitting mill. By the end of the Civil War — just eleven years later — he was a millionaire, having built a factoring house whose business grew sixteen-fold in four years of wartime demand."},{"number":2,"category":"character","header":"1907 Panic: silk top hat on Wall Street","body":"When the Panic of 1907 struck, the 72-year-old James arrived on Wall Street in his long-outmoded silk top hat and frock coat, carrying a list of securities and a pencil. When the market recovered, his fortunes were greatly increased — he had never speculated in his life, so he had capital ready when others were ruined."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"Bailed Republicans from Tammany jails every Election Day","body":"An ardent Republican since the birth of the party, James took every Election Day off. After voting, he went jail to jail across New York, bailing out any Republicans who had been locked up by corrupt Tammany Hall forces after being challenged at the polls."},{"number":4,"category":"legacy","header":"Tithed ten percent of his income, every year","body":"Throughout his career James gave at least ten percent of his income to charity. He funded Talcott Hall at Oberlin College (1887), an arboretum at Mount Holyoke, a library in West Hartford, and a hospital in China. With Dwight L."},{"number":5,"category":"legacy","header":"Died at Lake Mohonk's peace community in 1916","body":"James was a frequent speaker at the Lake Mohonk Conferences on International Arbitration, the peace and Native rights gatherings convened by the Smiley brothers from 1883 onward. He died at Lake Mohonk Mountain House on August 21, 1916, age eighty-one, in the community where he had spoken on peace for decades."}],"bio":{"display_name":"James Talcott","first_name":"James","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1777579998/850_James_Talcott_ipbmgm.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. Cloudinary."},"military_service":[],"slug":"james-talcott-1835"},"T01463":{"id":"T01463","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":true,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1866,"month":9,"day":14,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"year":1944,"month":2,"day":6,"city":"Manhattan","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM112","plot_notes":"Woodlawn Cemetery, Bronx NY. Cypress Plot, Sec 47, Grave 1. GPS: 40.8911853, -73.8694291."},"residence":{"city":"Manhattan","county":"New York","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"generation_from_john_talcott":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["business","arts","social_reform"],"notable_blurb":"Financier; National Arts Club president; highest etching award","primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Frederick_Talcott","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia"},"parents":{"father_id":"H03207","mother_id":"U00038"},"number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"I00192","date_year":1890,"date_month":10,"date_day":28,"location_city":"New York City","location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death_of_spouse","end_year":1915,"children_ids":["T01932","T01933","T01934"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_id":"I00193","date_year":1917,"date_month":1,"date_day":1,"location_state":"New York","location_country":"United States","end_type":"death","end_year":1944,"children_ids":[]}],"tags":["artist","businessman","deacon","etcher","hooker_talcott_descent"],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"career","header":"Princeton lacrosse champion — then ordained Episcopal minister","body":"J. Frederick Talcott graduated Princeton in 1888 as a champion lacrosse player, then studied theology at Oxford, traveled Egypt and Palestine, took an eleven-day horseback caravan into Syria, and returned to be ordained an Episcopal minister in 1893."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Grew the family business to $103 million","body":"After joining his father's factoring house in 1897, J. Frederick led its transformation from a merchandise-handling firm into a capital-lending institution. From 1926 to 1941, sales grew from $17 million to $103 million, guiding the company through the Depression without debt."},{"number":3,"category":"legacy","header":"Raised $400,000 for America's first Black college","body":"As trustee of Lincoln University — the nation's first degree-granting historically Black college and university — Talcott headed a $400,000 fundraising campaign in 1934 for a new library, dining hall, gymnasium, and assembly area. He also endowed the J. Frederick Talcott Award, once considered the nation's highest honor for etching in the United States."}],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — James Frederick Talcott","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Frederick_Talcott"},{"label":"J. Frederick Talcott obituary — New York Times, Feb 1944"}],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"title":"Deacon","first_name":"James","middle_name":"Frederick","last_name":"Talcott","married_names":[],"nickname":"J. Frederick","display_name":"Deacon James Frederick Talcott","photo_url":"https://images.findagrave.com/photos/2017/171/180587173_1498074668.jpg","photo_notes":"Portrait. FindAGrave."},"military_service":[],"slug":"james-talcott-1866"},"T01464":{"id":"T01464","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1868,"month":4,"day":8,"city":"West Hartford","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States"},"baptism":{},"death":{"month":1,"day":1,"country":"United States"},"burial":{},"residence":{"country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":true,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"generation_from_thomas":9,"generation_from_john_talcott":8,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"descent_paths_to_thomas":1,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":true,"is_progenitor":false,"is_ea